title: thread 'rustc' panicked at 'assertion failed: `(left == right)` when calling a trait method with more generic arguments than expected (nightly)

labels.name: I-ICE
labels.description: Issue: The compiler panicked, giving an Internal Compilation Error (ICE) ❄️

labels.name: regression-from-stable-to-nightly
labels.description: Performance or correctness regression from stable to nightly.

labels.name: T-compiler
labels.description: Relevant to the compiler team, which will review and decide on the PR/issue.

body:
### Code ```Rust pub trait Ice { fn f(&self); } impl Ice for () { fn f(&self) {} } fn main() { ().f::<()>(()); } ``` Repros on the [playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=nightly&mode=debug&edition=2021&gist=e7e689a8eec4e4a817ae9b33818e4279)/current nightly. But works (gives an error about mismatched number of generic arguments) on stable and beta. s/o to @memoryruins for the minimal example. ### Meta `rustc --version --verbose`: ``` rustc 1.65.0-nightly (84f0c3f79 2022-09-03) binary: rustc commit-hash: 84f0c3f79a85329dd79a54694ff8a7f427c842e9 commit-date: 2022-09-03 host: x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu release: 1.65.0-nightly LLVM version: 15.0.0 ``` ### Error output
